Question: Which of the following LaTeX code snippets correctly implements a system of equations with a right brace grouping x and y together, indicating they are both equal to a, while z is separately equal to b?

A) \begin{equation}
     \begin{cases}
       x = a \\
       y = a \\
       z = b
     \end{cases}
   \end{equation}

B) \begin{equation}
     \left\lbrace
     \begin{array}{l}
       x = a \\
       y = a \\
       z = b
     \end{array}
     \right.
   \end{equation}

C) \begin{equation}
     \left\lbrace
     \begin{array}{l}
       \left. 
       \begin{array}{c}
         x\\
         y
       \end{array}
       \right\rbrace = a\\
       z = b
     \end{array}
     \right.
   \end{equation}

D) \begin{equation}
     \begin{cases}
       x \\
       y \right\} = a \\
       z = b
     \end{cases}
   \end{equation}

Correct Answer: C

Explanation: Option C is the correct implementation. It uses nested arrays and braces to achieve the desired grouping. The outer \left\lbrace and \right. create the main brace, while the inner \left. and \right\rbrace group x and y together, showing they are both equal to a. The z = b is placed separately below this grouping. Options A and B don't provide the required grouping for x and y. Option D attempts to use the right brace within a cases environment, which is incorrect syntax and won't compile properly.

